1.¤The debtor must notify the creditor of any change of address. Such
notification may not be given on a credit transfer form if it is
stated on the form that it may not be used for notifications to the
payee. Notices requesting payment, including notices of termination, can
be sent or communicated by the creditor to the debtor's last
known address notwithstanding any subsequent change of address, unless
the creditor is aware of the debtor's new address. If the
creditor learns that, due to a change of address, a notice of
termination has not reached the debtor, the creditor must promptly
inform the debtor of the notice if the debtor's new address is
available from the National Registration Office (Folkeregisteret) or
any other easily accessible source.
.sp 5mm
.of
.of 4mm
2.¤The pledge comprises compensation and insurance sums which replace
the pledged assets, but not other surrogates. The pledge does not
comprise assets arising from the normal use of the pledge and
intended for separation, without this involving any actual usage of
the pledge, unless the assets are of a type which is comprised by the
pledge.
.sp 5mm
.of
.of 4mm
3.¤If the pledge is provided under Section 47c(3), Items 2, 3, 4, 5 or
6, of the Danish Land Registration Act (Tinglysningsloven), the
debtor is obliged to keep the pledge duly insured against fire.
.sp 5mm
.of
.of 4mm
4.¤Irrespective of whether the pledge can be terminated or whether
notice of termination is required, the creditor is entitled to demand
payment of the capital in the following circumstances:
.sp 3mm
.in 4mm
.of 3mm
a)¤¤if the pledge deteriorates significantly or is neglected without
adequate security being provided on demand,
.sp 3mm
.of 3mm
b)¤¤if the debtor refuses to grant the creditor or his agent access to
inspect the pledge,
.sp 3mm
.of
.of 3mm
c)¤¤if the debtor does not prove upon request that the pledge, if it is
provided under Section 47c(3), Items 2, 3, 4, 5 or 6, of the Danish
Land Registration Act, is duly insured against fire, and
.sp 3mm
.of
.of 3mm
d)¤¤if the pledge or elements of it of significance to the security of the
pledge are assigned to a third party, without this being regarded as
separation by virtue of the company's regular operations, or sold in a
compulsory sale.
